snippet.textDisplay: What I find sad is that people say "we support you in whatever you choose" and "we will love you regardless" but when the person chooses what you don't agree with, when Peter chose what his mother was against, then watch the ugly come out. Wasn't it HA, who just earlier commented on Peter's inability to realize the effect his words have on other people?  Guess where he learned it? ... I give Peter credit for making a choice he feels is best for him at this time. It might not be the right one, but he has full right to make it for himself. And, his parents should support him in it, not undermine it. He's almost 30, for heaven's sake!! Peter's uphill battle won't only be with Madison, but with his family as well. I hope he's strong enough to stay true to himself; we already know Madison will. One thing I have to say - people coming from different backgrounds, with differences in personality have found ways to make it work. Two likes don't always make a perfect couple; it's the struggles a couple go through together, and come out together on the other side that create a strong bond, real commitment. I'd rather two different people who work together and walk together define marriage than a couple like his parents, who we obviously can see who has control and power in that family! We need more children like Madison - who know who they are and stay true to that - and children like that come from parents that Madison and Peter have the potential to become.
